model_explanation: the sentence focuses on “ROB” receiving bananas, and S2 talks about Tom. The two sentences mention different recipients.
the prosodic focus on “TOM” and the exclusivity means Sam gave Tom grapes and nothing else. Therefore, it follows that Sam didn’t give Tom oranges.
the focus on “oranges” means Sam gave Sue only oranges, and yet S2 states Sam also gave Sue apples, which contradicts it.
S1 focuses on Sue receiving bananas, and says nothing about Rob. S2 independently talks about Rob not receiving bananas.
the focus on “oranges” means Tom only received oranges, so it logically follows that Tom didn’t get bananas.
the focus on “apples” shows that Sue only got apples, so Sue didn’t receive other items such as oranges.
the focus on “GRAPES” means Sue got only grapes, so she didn’t get apples.
the focus on “ELLEN” receiving only oranges is contradicted by S2, which says Ellen also got bananas.
the focus on “grapes” restricts what Mary got, and S2 says Mary didn’t get apples, which is consistent but not inferred directly, making them independent.
the focus on “BILL” receiving only oranges contradicts S2, which introduces a second person, Mary, also receiving oranges, breaking the exclusivity.
